{@--2@} Misfortune, trouble, calamity,
injury, harm; {#praSamitASezopasargAH#}
{#prajAH#} <ls>Ratn. 1. 10</ls>; {#sopasargaM vo nakzatraM#}  
<ls>M. 4.</ls>

{@--8@} A preposition 

prefixed to roots; {#nipAtAScAdayo jYeyAH#}
{#prAdayastUpasargakAH . dyotakatvAt kriyAyoge#}
{#lokAdavagatA ime ..#} {%Upasargas%} are 20
in number:-- {#pra, parA, apa, sam#},
{#anu, ava, nis#} or {#nir, dus#} or {#dur, vi, A#}
{#(N), ni, aDi, api, ati, su, ut, aBi#},
{#prati, pari, upa#}; or 22 if {#nis-nir#} and {#dus-dur#}
be taken as separate words. There
are two theories as to the character
of these prepositions. According to
one theory roots have various 
meanings in themselves ({#anekArTA hi DAtavaH#});
when prepositions are prefixed to
them they simply bring to light
those meanings already existent but
hidden in them, but they do not
{%express%} them, being meaningless
themselves; <ab>cf.</ab> <ls>Śi. 10. 15</ls>:-- {#saMtameva#}
{#ciramaprakftatvAdaprakASitamadidyutadaMge . viBramaM#} 
{#maDumadaH pramadAnAM DAtulInamupasarga ivArTam ..#}.
According to the other theory 
prepositions {%express%} their own 
independent meanings; they modify,
intensify, and sometimes entirely
alter, the senses of roots; <ab>cf.</ab> <ls>Sk.</ls>:  
--{#upasargeRa DAtvarTo balAdanyatra nIyate .#} 
{#prahArAhArasaMhAravihAraparihAravat ..#} <ab>cf.</ab> also {#DAtvarTaM bADate#}
{#kaScitkaScittamanuvartate . tameva viSinazwyanya#} 
{#upasargagatistriDA ..#} (The latter theory 
appears to be more correct. For a fuller
exposition see Nirukta).
